{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17508182","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17508182"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:03:07+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:03:07+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2732"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"2732","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/2732"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.24,0.57,0.01,0.04,0.14]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2732"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"23593"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"2732","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/2732"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2732"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"11898"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"4"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4174"},{"type":"tags","id":"4962"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"8218"},{"type":"tags","id":"11625"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"3513"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3515"},{"type":"contributions","id":"3616"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42560"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"23593","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/23593"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 70-year old male presents to his General Practitioner after noticing he has trouble breathing and his face flushes red when he lays flat. This began about two weeks ago.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination his vital signs are within normal range. He has no nail changes or tremor. He has a neck mass that is palpable, it has many multi-nodular components to it and the lower pole is not palpable with his neck hyper-extended. Percussion across his chest is dull and when he is asked to raise his hands above his head the following sign is observed (Image).\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely cause of his appearance?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Mediastinal tumour","Goitre","Aortic aneurysm","Mediastinal lymphadenopathy","Lung cancer"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EA positive Pemberton\u2019s sign occurs when there is a temporary superior vena cava obstruction and the process of raising the arms above the head obstructs the thoracic inlet. This is represented with the triad of trouble breathing, stridor and facial flushing. Additional symptoms can include conjunctival injection and dilated neck veins.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAll the above options can cause a superior vena cava obstruction and hence a positive Pemberton\u2019s sign. However, due to his other symptoms such as a neck lump and it\u0027s consistency, suggest a goitre as a cause.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ETraditionally, Pemberton\u2019s sign is done during a thyroid examination as retrosternal \u003Cstrong\u003Egoitres\u003C/strong\u003E can cause a positive result. The most common type of goitre that leads to this is a multinodular goitre that has grown slowly over many years. These types of goitres are large and can produce symptoms such as problems breathing, wheezing, cough, hoarse voice, stridor or dysphagia. They can also cause similar symptoms with changes in position such as lying flat or with neck movements. A CT scan should be ordered to show how far it extends and to guide management, which most often involves surgery.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA hilar \u003Cstrong\u003Elung cancer\u003C/strong\u003E is another pathology that can cause of a positive Pemberton\u2019s sign. If large enough compression of the thoracic inlet could occur. Again, this patient does not report any other findings consistent with this such as weight loss, cough and haemoptysis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn extremely large thoracic \u003Cstrong\u003Eaortic aneurysm\u003C/strong\u003E could cause a positive Pemberton\u2019s sign if it compressed the thoracic inlet. However, if it were large enough to do this the patient may display symptoms such as chest/back pain, and in the case of rupture the patient can become haemodynamically unstable. This would not explain the neck lump and this patient does not mention symptoms of chest/back pain.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Emediastinal tumour\u003C/strong\u003E is rare type of tumour. They can be benign or malignant, one cause is lymphoma. The lump in his neck could be consistent with a mediastinal tumour, however he does not display features of weight loss, night sweats, loss of appetite or fatigue that can be present in lymphoma.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Pemberton\u0027s sign is positive when a patient lifts their arms above their head and they demonstrate trouble breathing, facial flushing and stridor","Pemberton\u0027s sign suggests there is a mass obstructing the thoracic inlet (often a large restrosternal goitre)"],"references":["Clayman G. Substernal Goiter: Diagnosis and Treatment of Substeernal Goitre. Clayman Thyroid Centre. Access at: https://www.thyroidcancer.com/goiters/substernal-goiters.","Clift PF, Cervi E. A review of thoracic aortic aneurysm disease. Echo Res Pract. 2019;7(1):R1-R10. Published 2019 Dec 5. doi:10.1530/ERP-19-0049","Clayman G. Substernal Goiter: Diagnosis and Treatment of Substeernal Goitre. Clayman Thyroid Centre. Access at: https://www.thyroidcancer.com/goiters/substernal-goiters.","Nguyen A, Belderbos H, Harten J \u0026 Wijne L 2018. Superior vena cava syndrome presenting as position-dependent periortibital oedema. BMJ Case Reports. Access: http://dx.doi.org/10.1136/bcr-2018-225220","Nickson C 2020. SVC Obstruction DDx. Life In The Fast Lane. Access at: https://litfl.com/svc-obstruction-ddx/."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"11898"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"2732"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"15283"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"15283","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/15283"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/4e75a2f1-8802-4944-af50-6acefaaa2578.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/4e75a2f1-8802-4944-af50-6acefaaa2578.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":800,"height":600}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"11898","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/11898"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2022-04-30T09:09:46+09:30","updatedAt":"2022-04-30T09:09:47+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"2732"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"23593"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"4","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf6c","name":"Endocrinology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attribute